<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="126" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[811,1456,694,1581]" box="[813,919,694,720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[811,1456,694,1581]" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">
Because of the similar vegetative appearance, 
<bibRefCitation author="CHEN F. H. &amp; HU C. M." pageId="1" pageNumber="126" pagination="21 - 53" refId="ref1782" refString="CHEN F. H. &amp; HU C. M. 1979. - Taxonomic and phytogeographic studies on Chinese species of Lysimachia. Acta Phytotaxonomica Sinica 17 (4): 21 - 53." type="journal article" year="1979">Chen &amp; Hu (1979)</bibRefCitation>
assigned 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. H. Chen &amp; C. M. Hu" authorityYear="1979" box="[1002,1223,757,783]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rupestris">
<emphasis box="[1002,1223,757,783]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Lysimachia rupestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
together with 
<taxonomicName authority="Champ. ex Benth." authorityName="Benth." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alpestris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">L. alpestris</emphasis>
Champ. ex Benth.
</taxonomicName>
to subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[1246,1368,789,815]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1246,1368,789,815]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Lysimachia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section 
<emphasis box="[813,914,821,847]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Rosulatae</emphasis>
R. Knuth only according to the flower characters of 
<taxonomicName box="[841,956,853,879]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alpestris">
<emphasis box="[841,956,853,879]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">L. alpestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, i.e. the dorsifixed anthers opening by lateral slits, which is an important feature of subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[1328,1446,885,911]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1328,1446,885,911]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Lysimachia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although it also has short filaments connate basally into a very short ring and does not bear colored glands, which are the features of subgenus 
<emphasis box="[1122,1238,980,1006]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Idiophyton</emphasis>
Hand.-Mazz. 
<bibRefCitation author="BENNELL A. P. &amp; HU C. M." pageId="1" pageNumber="126" pagination="425 - 458" refId="ref1746" refString="BENNELL A. P. &amp; HU C. M. 1983. - The pollen morphology and taxonomy of Lysimachia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden, Edinburgh 40: 425 - 458." type="journal article" year="1983">Bennell &amp; Hu (1983)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[1331,1455,1012,1038]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1331,1455,1012,1038]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Lysimachia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section 
<emphasis box="[898,1001,1044,1070]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Rosulatae</emphasis>
could be derived directly from subgenus 
<emphasis box="[811,928,1076,1102]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Idiophyton</emphasis>
section 
<taxonomicName box="[1020,1159,1076,1102]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Apodanthera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1020,1159,1076,1102]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Apodanthera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on pollen morphology. Recent phylogenetic research confirmed that section 
<emphasis box="[812,914,1140,1166]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Rosulatae</emphasis>
is more close to subgenus 
<emphasis box="[1202,1318,1140,1166]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Idiophyton</emphasis>
, rather than subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[927,1049,1172,1198]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[927,1049,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Lysimachia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="HAO G. &amp; YUAN Y. M. &amp; HU C. M. &amp; GE X. J. &amp; ZHAO N. X." box="[1068,1252,1172,1198]" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" pagination="323 - 339" refId="ref1818" refString="HAO G., YUAN Y. M., HU C. M., GE X. J. &amp; ZHAO N. X. 2004. - Molecular phylogeny of Lysimachia (Myrsinaceae) based on chloroplast trn L-F and nuclear ribosomal ITS sequences. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 31: 323 - 339. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 1055 - 7903 (03) 00286 - 0" type="journal article" year="2004">
Hao 
<emphasis box="[1127,1184,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
; Anderberg 
<emphasis box="[1399,1456,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">et al.</emphasis>
2007). Our supplement of the floral characters, especially the basifixed anthers opening by apical pores (
<figureCitation box="[1359,1444,1236,1262]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="2.[132,143,1985,2003]" captionTargetBox="[201,1382,214,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-104@2.[194,1393,207,1923]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIG. 1. — Lysimachia rupestris Chen &amp; C.M.Hu (Nian He Xia, Viet Lam Le &amp; Duy Hung Vuong, s.n. [IBSC]):A, habit;B, glands on leaves;C, leaf base;D, calyx;E, flower with corolla removed;F, corolla opened up showing stamens;G, fruit.Drawing:Ding-han Cui. Scale bars:A, 2 cm; B, C, not to scale; D, 5 mm;E, F,4 mm;G, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4599116" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4599116/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Fig. 1F</figureCitation>
) of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="F. H. Chen &amp; C. M. Hu" authorityYear="1979" box="[844,966,1268,1293]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rupestris">
<emphasis box="[844,966,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">L. rupestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is another strong evidence to support that section 
<emphasis box="[902,1006,1299,1325]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Rosulatae</emphasis>
should be transferred to subgenus 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">Idiophyton</emphasis>
. The third species with the spirally aggregated leaves forming nearly rosettes is the recently described 
<taxonomicName authority="(Phan &amp; Hu 2011)" baseAuthorityName="Phan &amp; Hu" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[813,1212,1395,1422]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="verbascifolia">
<emphasis box="[813,979,1395,1421]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">L. verbascifolia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="PHAN K. L. &amp; HU C. M." box="[997,1200,1395,1422]" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" pagination="601 - 604" refId="ref2142" refString="PHAN K. L. &amp; HU C. M. 2011. - Lysimachia vietnamensis and L. verbascifolia spp. nov. (Primulaceae) from Vietnam. Nordic Journal of Botany 29: 601 - 604. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1756 - 1051.2011.01174. x" type="journal article" year="2011">Phan &amp; Hu 2011</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This species also has basifixed anthers opening by apical pores, which shows its affinity of 
<taxonomicName box="[969,1082,1460,1485]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Primulaceae" genus="Lysimachia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="1" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rupestis">
<emphasis box="[969,1082,1460,1485]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="126">L. rupestis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the lack of stolons in 
